data.name: Label1.Text
data.value:
Taurus is hard to miss as he charges through the northern winter sky, fascinating generations of astronomers. Taurus, or ‘The Bull’, is one of the most noticeable constellations, and one of the oldest- descriptions of Taurus go back as far as the early bronze age. In the northern hemisphere, the bull passes through the sky from November to March, but it’s most visible in January.
In Greek mythology, Taurus was identified with Zeus, who assumed the form of a white bull to abduct Europa, a princess. In illustrations of the myth, Zeus in bull form is partially submerged in the sea as he stole Europa away, in order to hide from his wife Hera. Other myths ascribe the constellation to that of the Cretan Bull, who the hero Hercules had to conquer in order to fulfill one of his Twelve Labors.
The giant red star in Taurus, named Albebaran, is 65 light-years away from Earth. It’s the brightest star in the constellation, and the 14th brightest in the sky.
